xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2371:"<p class="MsoNormal"><i>Bowman v. Monsanto</i>\nis just the latest of many patent cases that has found its way to the Supreme\nCourt''s docket. The question posed to the court was, essentially, what\nconstitutes infringement of a patent to a patented gene in a plant, that inevitably\nwill be planted and will reproduce itself. Also at issue is when those rights\nare "exhausted".&nbsp; The <a href="http://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/11-796.pdf">oral\narguments</a>&nbsp;took place this Tuesday, February 19, 2013.</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal">Bowman started the day on the defensive. While Justice\nStevens may have gotten top billing for his joking comment referencing Justice\nOliver Wendell Holmes'' infamous words in <i>Buck\nv. Bell</i> positing that, "[m]aybe three generations of seeds is\nenough," Chief Justice Roberts'' opening question seemed to mirror the\nfeelings of the rest of the Court. He bluntly said, " Why in the world would\nanybody spend any money to try to improve the seed if as soon as they sold the\nfirst one anybody could grow more and have as many of those seeds as they want?"\nAnd indeed that was the question every Justice on the Court wanted answered.</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal">While it may have started out in jest, Breyer''s three\ngenerations argument was not limited to the realm of entertainment. It was the\nbasis of a significant number of his questions including saying, "The only\nthing he cannot do is he cannot create generation 3, just as he couldnt use\ngeneration 2 seeds to rob a bank." Justice Ginsberg also liked Breyer''s\ncategorization saying, "theres another law that says you cannot make\ncopies of a patented invention. And that\nlaw you have violated when you use [generation 2] to make generation 3."</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal">While at times the Court attempted to give Bowman''s\nattorney, Mark Walters, the opportunity to draw an analogy to other\nself-replicating technologies, he never fully explored this path. There may\nhave been a Hail-Mary lifeline out there somewhere in the form of software\npatents (perhaps in a RAM-ROM copying analogy), but that is all it is, a long\nshot. Bowman certainly had an uphill climb coming in, and it looks no smaller\nafter Tuesday.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 23 Feb 2013 15:10:44 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:24:"\n			\n			\n			\n\n			\n			\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:26:"RIPL&#039;s 2013 Symposium";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"http://www.jmripl.com.php5-10.dfw1-2.websitetestlink.com/blog/post/34";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"http://www.jmripl.com.php5-10.dfw1-2.websitetestlink.com/blog/post/34";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1797:"<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0px; color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 13px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"></p><p class="MsoNormal">RIPL is excited to announce its fourth annual\nsymposium.&nbsp; This years topic is IP Rights, Ownership and Identity in\nSocial Media. &nbsp;The Keynote Address will be delivered by John Corvino,\nGeneral Counsel for the Chicago White Sox, and Tony McShane, Partner at the\nChicago-based firm Neal, Gerber &amp; Eisenberg.&nbsp; Additional speakers\ninclude the Honorable James Holderman, Chief Judge for the Northern District of\nIllinois; Dr. Saby Ghoshray, esteemed author and Vice President for Development\nand Compliance at WorldCompliance Company; Professor Lucille Ponte from the\nUniversity of Central Florida College of Health &amp; Public Affairs; Professor\nMary Penrose from Texas Wesleyan School of Law; Keidra Chaney, Digital\nStrategist; Jennifer Gregory of Jenner &amp; Block; and Raizel Liebler, law\nlibrarian for The John Marshall Law School.</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal">The symposium will be held at the 12th Floor Conference\nCenter at The John Marshall Law School on Friday, April 5, 2013.&nbsp;\nRegistration and breakfast begin at 8 a.m., with presentations to follow\nshortly thereafter.&nbsp; Each attendee will be provided with lunch and a flash\ndrive comprising all symposium materials.&nbsp; Attendees can also obtain\napproximately 5.5 hours of CLE credit.&nbsp; Click&nbsp;<a href="http://events.jmls.edu/registration/node/315" target="_blank">here</a>&nbsp;to\nregister, or contact RIPLs Symposium Editor, Tricia Brauer, at&nbsp;<a href="mailto:tbrauer@law.jmls.edu" target="_blank">tbrauer@law.jmls.edu</a>.&nbsp;\nWe look forward to seeing you at what will be a most interesting event!</p><p></p>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 14 Feb 2013 20:59:58 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:24:"\n			\n			\n			\n\n			\n			\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"RIPL 12-1 Is now online";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17: